[1]
Date: 26 Oct 2015
From: Louise Taylor <info@rabiesalliance.org> [edited]


We would like to respond to the posting below from Merritt Clifton published on ProMED on 22 Oct 2015 (PRO/AH> Rabies - Indonesia (09): (BA) canine, comment, Archive Number: 20151022.3735706).

Our response is this: "On the subject of numbers of human rabies deaths in India, we would refer the interested reader to peer-reviewed publications rather than their interpretation and misrepresentation as presented in this thread.

Table 1 from the 2003 WHO-sponsored National Multicentric Rabies Survey (Sudarshan et al., 2007) reported between 300 and 400 human rabies deaths per year (from 1992-2002) from the records of 22 infectious disease hospitals, and between 700-900 probable cases based on clinical criteria from these same hospitals. Over half of the patients classified as probable cases left these hospitals against medical advice so were not recorded as deaths.

In contrast to the reporting in this thread, the 235 deaths in this study were the rabies deaths identified by follow up community-based surveys, calculated to cover a population of 10.8 million. Of these, the majority (79.1 percent) did not receive any post-exposure vaccine and, therefore, did not access health services.

The aim of the multicentric study was to estimate the incidence of human rabies in India based on the most reliable data from these community surveys (to reduce the effect of recall bias). The study abstract reports: "The annual incidence of human rabies was estimated to be 17 137 (95 percent CI 14 109 to 20 165). Based on expert group advice, an additional 20 percent was added to this to include paralytic/atypical forms of rabies, providing an estimate of 20 565 or about 2 per 100 000 population."

A more recent independent study based on verbal autopsy suggested that in 2005, there were 12 700 (99 percent CI 10 000 to 15 500) symptomatically identifiable furious rabies deaths in India (Suraweera et al., 2012).

These are estimates extrapolated from extensive investigations but nonetheless representing only a sample of India's overall population. The findings of more recent global modelling studies are also based on extrapolations from limited data (GBD Mortality Causes of Death Collaborators, 2014; Hampson et al., 2015). As expected, given their different methods and underlying data sources, the point estimates of human rabies deaths in these studies differ. Nonetheless, all estimate that tens of thousands of human rabies deaths occur in India each year.

Rabies is a fatal disease. People who arrive at a hospital leave when there is no treatment that can be offered. Moreover, the 22 hospitals in this study were accessible to only a small fraction of rabies victims throughout India. Active surveillance has identified considerable underreporting of rabies (as evidenced by the Sudarshan and other studies around the world). Until official surveillance data are reliable enough for accurate recording of human rabies cases in canine rabies-endemic countries, estimates are, sadly, the best information that we have. Relying on recorded data known to be inadequate and not using all available information severely under-represents the scale of the rabies problem and does a disservice to the victims of rabies globally.

Misrepresenting evidence is misleading, and repeating the same assertions does not make them true. Rather, it risks the reputation of the ProMED forum as a source of reliable information to the global health community.

References
-------
GBD Mortality Causes of Death Collaborators. (2014). Global, regional, and national age-sex specific all-cause and cause-specific mortality for 240 causes of death, 1990-2013: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2013. Lancet. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61682-2.

Hampson, K., Coudeville, L., Lembo, T., Sambo, M., Kieffer, A., Attlan, M. Global Alliance for Rabies Control Partners for Rabies, P. (2015). Estimating the global burden of endemic canine rabies. PLoS Negl Trop Dis, 9(4), e0003709. doi: 10.1371/journal.pntd.0003709.

Sudarshan, M. K., Madhusudana, S. N., Mahendra, B. J., Rao, N. S., Ashwath Narayana, D. H., Abdul Rahman, S. Gangaboraiah. (2007). Assessing the burden of human rabies in India: results of a national multi-center epidemiological survey. Int J Infect Dis, 11(1), 29-35. doi: 10.1016/j.ijid.2005.10.007.

Suraweera, W., Morris, S. K., Kumar, R., Warrell, D. A., Warrell, M. J., Jha, P., & Million Death Study, C. (2012). Deaths from symptomatically identifiable furious rabies in India: a nationally representative mortality survey. PLoS Negl Trop Dis, 6(10), e1847. doi: 10.1371/journal.pntd.0001847.

