Date: 26 Oct 2015
From: Merritt Clifton <animals24.7@frontier.com> [edited]


First of all, we have already been around almost exactly this same mulberry bush several times before, most recently on 18-23 Apr 2015; see 20150420.3309817.

My focal point then was that where 17 000 or 20 000 or 21 000 bodies were claimed to exist, fewer than 250 could be found. The burden of proof is on the persons making the claim to find them. Exercises in math based on presumptive projection are no substitute for forensic evidence in bringing a murder charge, and should not be substituted for forensic evidence in allocating resources in disease control either.

The only noteworthy addition to Louise Taylor's argument is that she has shifted from relying on GARC's own publications, which are based on presumptive projection, to relying on Suraweera W, Morris SK, Kumar R, et al, in "Deaths from Symptomatically Identifiable Furious Rabies in India: A Nationally Representative Mortality Survey. 2012: PLoS Negl Trop Dis 6 (10); e1847. doi:10.1371/journal.pntd.0001847," which is also based on presumptive projection.

Suraweera et al used a survey method called "verbal autopsy," which in law would be called relying on hearsay, and in reputable journalism would be called relying on 2nd-hand sources.

The "verbal autopsy" method consisted basically of asking people: "Did anyone in your family die within the past couple of years, and if so, from what?"

Unlike an actual autopsy, no body was present. No one with actual diagnostic or forensic expertise confirmed the symptoms with any sort of testing of physical evidence. Deaths were simply presumed to be more-or-less from whatever the respondents said they were from.

What happens when one interviews anyone after the fact about anything? First of all, there is a high margin of error, no matter what is being described, because memories are inexact. The more complex the subject, the higher the margin of error becomes. The margin of error is multiplied further when the interviewees are poorly educated, perhaps even illiterate, and not familiar with the range of plausible explanations for the observed phenomena.

Under that circumstance, the interviewees typically reach for the explanation familiar to them (history of dog bite within several months, high fever, followed by death = rabies, well-known and widely publicized in India for more than 150 years) instead of the explanation less familiar to them (history of mosquito bites, which everyone gets often and tends to not remember, high fever, followed by death = Japanese encephalitis, probably occurring in India for decades but only relatively recently medically recognized and still practically unknown to most of the public.)

Given the reality that mosquito bites outnumber dog bites in India by many millions to one, a statement like this from Taylor means nothing at all: "In contrast to the reporting in this thread, the 235 deaths in this study were the rabies deaths identified by follow up community-based surveys, calculated to cover a population of 10.8 million. Of these, the majority (79.1 percent) did not receive any post-exposure vaccine and, therefore, did not access health services."

If the cause of death was something transmitted by mosquitoes, such as Japanese encephalitis, or by any other insect or tick vector for febrile disease (to name just a couple of possibilities), whether the victims received post-exposure vaccination for rabies would be completely irrelevant.

Again, I want to see a "writ of rabies corpus:" show us the bodies.

--
Merritt Clifton
Editor
Greenbank, Washington, USA
http://www.Animals24-7.org
<Animals24.7@frontier.com>

[Patently, we have a definition difference for a case of human rabies in a situation where public health records are not as rigorous as one might hope for, though the pathology is sound. But I think we can agree that if canine rabies were properly controlled in India, as it has been in many counties, it would cease to be a public health problem or even a veterinary problem. This is long, long overdue.

I must reluctantly cut this thread at this point and leave it to my academic colleagues to continue it in their graduate classrooms, because their students will face the realities in their future professional lives. - Mod.MHJ]

[I would add that while completely accurate counts of human rabies cases are unlikely to be found in the developing world where most cases occur, the overwhelmingly prevalent view of global health authorities in both the human and animal sectors favors the higher estimates put forth by the Global Alliance for Rabies Control in the correspondence from Louise Taylor and Katie Hampson. Peer reviewed literature also appears to support these alarmingly high estimates.

Until further evidence develops, we will cut this thread. - Mod.LM

